      "rationale": "Bench-top experiments were conducted with bovine blood at 37 °C, 1500–3500 RPM, and 2–6 L/min flow. Temperature, hematocrit (40 ± 1%), and rotational speed (±5 RPM) were logged continuously. CFD boundary conditions replicate these values; deviations are within instrument uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH index must agree with measured RH within 15% at each of the 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted versus measured relative hemolysis index shows a maximum discrepancy of 9.2% and mean absolute error of 4.3% across the five operating points. All predictions fall within the 15% acceptance band, and no systematic bias is observed across the flow-speed combinations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (RH index) must be the same metric used in the regulatory decision.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index (RH) is both the validation metric and the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 compared to predicate). The QoI is therefore directly relevant to the COU without transformation or surrogate mapping."
    },
    {
